Check [\[Python 3.Docs\]: Built-in functions - **next**(*iterator\[, default\]*)](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#next). You have absolutely no need to call it.

**Note**: you are shadowing a couple of builtin names like *dict*, *input*. Don&#39;t do that, as you might experience (funky) errors as your codebase grows.

Your uncompressed form works, but not because of what you think. Calling *next* is redundant and useless. Your loop is equivalent to:

&lt;!-- language-all: python --&gt;

    for i in input_list:
        if i in dictionary:
            output += (dictionary[i] + &quot; &quot;)

As for the compressed form, you meant:

    output += (dictionary[i] + &quot; &quot;) if i in dictionary else &quot;&quot;  # NOT next

But you could do even better: a single line having a list comprehension, wrapped by a string:

    output = &quot; &quot;.join([dictionary[i] for i in input_list if i in dictionary])

and from there, the whole function could look like (by getting rid of the helper dictionary, and using a property of (lower case letter) characters *ASCII* codes):

    def alphabet_position(text):
        return &quot; &quot;.join(str(ord(c) - 0x60) for c in text.lower() if c.islower())

If you replace next with a `&#39;&#39;`, your code works fine:

    for i in input:
        output += (dict[i]+&quot; &quot;) if i in dict else &#39;&#39;

I&#39;m not sure what next is supposed to be, but it isn&#39;t a python keyword.

